definition: "Zinc is an essential trace mineral that serves as a structural component or catalytic cofactor in over 300 enzymes and more than 2,000 transcription factors. It is the second most abundant trace mineral in the human body after iron. Zinc is required for DNA synthesis and repair, protein synthesis, cell division, immune cell development and function, wound healing, taste and smell, and the production of testosterone and other hormones. Because the body has no dedicated zinc storage system — unlike iron (ferritin) or vitamin D (adipose tissue) — zinc status depends entirely on ongoing dietary intake, making deficiency relatively common when diet is suboptimal or absorption is impaired."
why_it_matters: "Zinc occupies a unique position in longevity biology because its deficiency simultaneously impairs three of the most consequential aging-related systems: immune function, DNA repair capacity, and anabolic hormone production. Zinc deficiency accelerates immunosenescence — the progressive deterioration of immune function with age — by impairing T-cell development and natural killer cell activity. It impairs the DNA damage response, potentially accelerating genomic instability. And it reduces testosterone biosynthesis in men, contributing to the age-associated testosterone decline. Estimates suggest that 17–20% of the global population is at risk for zinc deficiency, with higher rates in older adults, vegetarians, people with gastrointestinal disorders, and heavy alcohol users."

